	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0036">36<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-04/ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0036.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div id="PJA04d022" class="doc letter">

    <h1>From Joseph Palmer</h1>
    
    <div class="docbody">
     <div class="opener">
      <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">My dear Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Watertown, Febry 19th. 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
     </div>
     <p>Your Family were pretty well yesterday; also Mr. Cranches and mine; N Q<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n1" id="PJA04d022n1-ptr">1</a> has a bad cold. I have been sick a few days, but am now better, so as to be abroad again.</p>
     <p>Yesterday a Gentleman arrived here, said to be a Prussian Knight, from France to the W Indies, thence bound to Philadelphia, but brot on upon the back of the Cape, from thence hither, and now at head Quarters, has many Letters for Dr. Franklin, a Packet for the President of the Congress, and another for the Secretary of ditto.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n2" id="PJA04d022n2-ptr">2</a> Tis Supposed that the Vessel was bound into Boston, tho he took passage for Philadelphia. Tis likely you will know more about it before you receive this. The Enemy threaten us hard at Braintree; but I hope to rouse the Sleeping Bear: Our Companies there<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n3" id="PJA04d022n3-ptr">3</a> have done hard duty, and are Somwhat discouraged by not having been commissionated; but I expect to obtain Commissions for em this Week, and to get a Major appointed over the 4 Companies: S Spear<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n4" id="PJA04d022n4-ptr">4</a> is moving off the Women and Children, and I expect others will move; but if the enemy dont attack us there, within 2 or 3 days, we Shall Stop the panic, <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0037">[37<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-04/ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0037.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>which is not great. I have Stolen a few hours from the Night, one time and another, to draw some imperfect Plans of Forts, and have presented them to the Court, in order to lead them to think seriously of making proper defences for Magazines, Harbours &amp;c.</p>
     <p>I heartily thank you for your present of common Sense; it is very welcom, and I believe no person was ever more eagerly read, nor more generally approved: People Speak of it in rapturous praise. Union among ourselves, and independency respecting Europe, seems to be the ardent wish of almost all. One of the Halls is dead, and the other dangerous, otherways it would have been re-printed: I intend to Speak to Edes about it tomorrow; it woud admit of a large impression.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n5" id="PJA04d022n5-ptr">5</a></p>
    </div>
    <div class="docbody">
     <div class="dateline">
      20th
     </div>
     <p>Ive heard more about this Stranger, Monsr. LeBaron &amp;c. &amp;c. &amp;c. He is a native of Dantzick, has been many years in the K of Prussias Service, is one of the Knights of Malta, has 2 Letters for Dr. F., one for Mr. Secretary Thomson, and many others; he is a Gentleman and a Politician; and says, that all Europe wish our Prosperity; and that the House of Bourbon in particular wish the Colonies to declare for independency, so that they may have nothing to fear from the English. The Baron took passage at the Mole,<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n6" id="PJA04d022n6-ptr">6</a> in a French Vessel bound to Philadelphia, as he understood it; but I suppose she was bound for Nantuckett; and we are credibly informed, that there are 6 or 7 more soon expected: There not being English Vessels to take off their Melasses, they send it in their own Bottoms. This Vessel was loaded with Melasses, and 1 hhd. Sugar; she got upon the Sholes within Sight of Nantuckett, lost both Anchors and Cables, and great part of her Sails, and then drifted on upon the back of Chatham; both Vessel and Cargo will be saved, as tis supposed.</p>
     <p>I dont particularly recollect what I wrote to you in my last;<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n7" id="PJA04d022n7-ptr">7</a> but since that time, conversation has much turnd upon Independency; and after having considered the matter as fully as opportunity admited, I am Satisfied in my mind, that this Colony woud rejoice most heartily in a Declaration by Congress in favor of it; and it is clear in my mind, that, upon such a Declaration, Trade ought to be regulated so that we may be our own Carriers; this will encourage Ship building, be a nursery for Sea-Men, and will prevent Foreigners obtaining any great knowledge of our Coasts and Harbours; and if possible, and I think tis possible, let us not enter into any Treaty offensive and defensive, with any European Power, so that we may avoid being involved in their Wars. I depend upon it, that if we <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0038">[38<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-04/ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0038.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>declare for independency, F and S will soon attack G B, but they will not do it till the breach between her and the Colonies is incurable. In the mean time we Shall grow in Military Strength and Knowledge, and once the Enemy are dislodged from Boston, and we can obtain a Sufficient Stock of Powder and other military Stores, there will be very little danger of their ever possessing it again; for it cant be long before our own Manufactures will furnish all necessary Stores in the Military way; and inspired by our cause, we Shall very soon equal, if not exceed Our Enemies in Military knowledge. The infamous Colo. Jones of W is dead;<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n8" id="PJA04d022n8-ptr">8</a> tis said that he was reduced very poor, and that his Widow is ill, and also poor: I feel for their distresses, notwithstanding their wickedness: I believe we had not a more inveterate enemy; had his power been = [<ins title="editorial addition or explanation" class="ed">equal</ins>] to his will, he would have matched a H<span title="text unclear" class="unclear">[u]</span>n. The enemy have burnt 6 or 7 Houses on Dorchester Neck, and stolen two or 3 of the Guards.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="docbody">
     <div class="dateline">
      24th
     </div>
     <p>Since the above, the Night before last, our people Stole a Corporal and 2 privates who were Centinels at the ruins of Browns House on the Neck; tis said that there was not a Gun fired, our folks Steping in between the 2 Centinels, took off, in a Storm, the outermost, without any alarm.</p>
     <p>Our Court is adjourned to the 13th Mar:; in the recess I am to go to Middletown in order to obtain further knowledge of Smelting &amp;c.</p>
     <p>I am to inclose to Mr. Hancock, the Report of the Committee upon Lead &amp;c., which is not reported in full, as you will See.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n9" id="PJA04d022n9-ptr">9</a> We are endeavouring to obtain, in the recess, all the late Acts of Court, and such Resolves as may be thot useful for the Congress, in order to transmit em thither as soon as possible.</p>
     <p>This is <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">the time</span>, for declaring independency; we never have had such a favourable moment before, and tis not likely we ever Shall have such another, if we neglect this: Such a Declaration, with a good Test-Act, will be a foundation to build a good Constitution upon; without these, many will be Squinting at the Constitution of 63;<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n10" id="PJA04d022n10-ptr">10</a> and so long as men (I ask pardon for calling em so) have an Eye to <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Such</span> a reconsiliation, they never will act with firmness and Spirit against our enemies. I fell into chat, this day, with Majr. F of N,<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d022n11" id="PJA04d022n11-ptr">11</a> who is a retailer of other Mens politicks; and when Speaking of independency, he asked whether Such a declaration woud not make G B more angry, and more determined to execute their Plans upon us: Such Questions have a bad tendency, which is very obvious, but a Declaration for Independence woud put a total Stop to all Questions of <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0039">[39<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-04/ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0039.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>this kind. I have not time to add, only that I remain with great affect., my dear Sir, Yr. Frd. and Servt:,</p>
     <div class="closer">
      <p class="signed">J P</p>
     </div>
    </div>
    <div class="docback">
     <div class="note-source" id="PJA04d022sn1">
      
   <p>
       <span class="docSource"><span class="dType"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr></span> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>); addressed: The Honble: John Adams Esqr. Philadelphia per favr. Majr. Osgood; docketed: Palmer Feby 19. 1776.</span>
      </p>

     </div>
     <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n1-ptr" id="PJA04d022n1">1</a>
      
   <p>For Norton Quincy (17161801), see sketch in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Diary and Autobiography of John Adams&lt;/i&gt;, ed. L. H. Butterfield and others, Cambridge, 1961; 4 vols. ]">JA, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diary and Autobiography</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-01-01-02-0010-0002-0001&amp;expandNote=DJA01d392n2#DJA01d392n2" class="document">1:302</a>, and <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Langdon Sibley and Clifford K. Shipton, &lt;i&gt;Biographical Sketches of Graduates of Harvard University, in Cambridge, Massachusetts&lt;/i&gt;, Cambridge and Boston, 1873 ]">Sibley-Shipton, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Harvard Graduates</span></span>, 10:7578.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n2-ptr" id="PJA04d022n2">2</a>
      
   <p>Baron Frederick William de Woedtke (ca. 17401776), who is further described later in the letter. See also <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Journals of the House of Representatives of Massachusetts&lt;/i&gt; [[1715-]], Boston, reprinted by the Massachusetts Historical Society, 1919-. (For the years for which reprints are not yet available, the original printings are cited, by year and session.) ]">Mass., <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">House Jour.</span></span>, 17751776, 3d sess., p. 309310. On 9 March the Baron arrived in Philadelphia with several letters of introduction (for those to Franklin see <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ [[Peter Force, ed.,]] &lt;i&gt;American Archives: Consisting of a Collection of Authentick Records, State Papers, Debates, and Letters and Other Notices of Publick Affairs&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 18371853; 9 vols. ]">Force, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Archives</span></span>, 4th ser., 5:410411) and apparently made a good impression, for a few days later <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> successfully moved that he be made a brigadier general. He was ordered to join the Northern Army, in which service he died, near Lake George in July (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ James Grant Wilson and John Fiske, eds., &lt;i&gt;Appletons' Cyclopaedia of American Biography&lt;/i&gt;, New York, 18871889; 6 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Appletons Cyclo. Amer. Biog.</span></span>; Richard Smiths Diary, 15, 16 March 1776, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Edmund C. Burnett, ed., &lt;i&gt;Letters of Members of the Continental Congress&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 19211936; 8 vols. ]">Burnett, ed., <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letters of Members</span></span>, 1:394, 395; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington C. Ford and others, eds., &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress&lt;/i&gt;, 17741789, Washington, 19041937; 34 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:209210; <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Pennsylvania Gazette</span>, 13 March 1776).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n3-ptr" id="PJA04d022n3">3</a>
      
   <p>For the four companies at Braintree, see Josiah Quincy to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-03-02-0198" class="document">2 Jan</a>. (above).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n4-ptr" id="PJA04d022n4">4</a>
      
   <p>Probably Seth Spear (17411818) of Braintree (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Quincy Patriot</span>, 24 Jan. 1885; see also <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Diary and Autobiography of John Adams&lt;/i&gt;, ed. L. H. Butterfield and others, Cambridge, 1961; 4 vols. ]">JA, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diary and Autobiography</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-01-04-02-0001-0002" class="document">4:6</a>).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n5-ptr" id="PJA04d022n5">5</a>
      
   <p>Ebenezer Hall, who died on 14 Feb., and his brother Samuel published the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">New England Chronicle</span> at Cambridge (Clarence S. Brigham, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">History and Bibliography of American Newspapers</span>, Worcester, 1947, 1:353). Copies of <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Common Sense</span>, probably the Philadelphia edition, were available for sale at least as early as 4 March, when they were advertised in the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Boston Gazette.</span> The first Massachusetts edition was advertised as published this day in the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Boston Gazette</span> of 22 April.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n6-ptr" id="PJA04d022n6">6</a>
      
   <p>Le Moule, Guadeloupe.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n7-ptr" id="PJA04d022n7">7</a>
      
   <p>Palmer to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-03-02-0213" class="document">23 Jan.</a> (above).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n8-ptr" id="PJA04d022n8">8</a>
      
   <p>Probably Col. Elisha Jones (17101776) of Weston (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Town of Weston, Births, Deaths and Marriages, 17071850</span> . . . , Boston, 1901, p. 1; Brenton H. Dickson and Homer C. Lucas, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">One Town in the American Revolution: Weston, Massachusetts</span>, Weston, 1976, p. 3643).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n9-ptr" id="PJA04d022n9">9</a>
      
   <p>The report of this committee, of which Palmer was a member, is printed in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Journals of the House of Representatives of Massachusetts&lt;/i&gt; [[1715-]], Boston, reprinted by the Massachusetts Historical Society, 1919-. (For the years for which reprints are not yet available, the original printings are cited, by year and session.) ]">Mass., <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">House Jour.</span></span>, 17751776, 3d sess., p. 304305. The council successfully offered an amendment to have it transmitted to the congress even though it was incomplete (same, p. 308).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n10-ptr" id="PJA04d022n10">10</a>
      
   <p>That is, the relations existing between Great Britain and the colonies before 1764. Colonists of whatever persuasion felt that that arrangement had been profoundly altered with the passage of the revenue measures. Moderates continued to hope that reconciliation could be based on a return to conditions that existed in 1763.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d022n11-ptr" id="PJA04d022n11">11</a>
      
   <p>Possibly Abraham Fuller (17201794) of Newton, who was a major in the militia (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ L. Kinvin Wroth, George H. Nash III, and Joel Meyerson, eds., &lt;i&gt;Province in Rebellion&lt;/i&gt;, Cambridge, 1975. ]">Wroth and others, eds., <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Province in Rebellion</span></span>, p. 2856).</p>

     </div>
